Insight 1.1.4 . Homogeneous systems. Consider a homogeneous system of linear equations,  egin{equation*}  A{A}  A{x} =  A{0}. \end{equation*} If \(\detA{ A{A}} 
e 0\) then we know that the system has unique solution. However, \( A{x} =  A{0}\) is always a solution to a homogeneous system. This implies that having \(\detA{ A{A}} 
e 0\) for a homogeneous system means that the only solution is \( A{x} =  A{0}	ext{.}\) Alternatively, if \(\detA{ A{A}} = 0\) then the system might have infinitely many solutions, meaning a \( A{x} 
e  A{0}\) is also a solution.

